# Core Security and Privacy

- Never hardcode or expose secrets (API keys, tokens, passwords, certs, DB URIs) in
 code, logs, tests, docs, commits, screenshots, or examples.
- Use environment variables or a dedicated secret manager for sensitive configuration.
- Never use real production data or PII in development artifacts; use synthetic or
 anonymized data only. Safe placeholders: `test@example.com`, `John Doe`, fake UUIDs.
- Validate and sanitize all untrusted input on the server side; never rely on
 client-side validation alone.
- Defend against: SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, command injection, path traversal,
 SSRF, and insecure deserialization.
- Enforce authentication and authorization on all protected operations using the
 principle of least privilege.
- Never perform destructive or irreversible operations (deletes, drops, bulk updates,
 secret rotations) without explicit user approval.
